{
  "slug": "the-10-most-anticipated-movies-of-summer-2024-plus-tarantino",
  "title": "The 10 Most Anticipated Movies of Summer 2024. Plus: Tarantino’s Pivot, Scorsese’s Sinatra, and Spielberg’s UFOs.",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2024-04-19",
  "runtimeMin": 86,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda work through a week of movie news (Tarantino shelving his 10th film, Scorsese's Sinatra biopic, Spielberg's next UFO movie), then each counts down five most-anticipated releases of summer 2024.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Movie News",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Once Upon a Time in Hollywood",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Deadline and The Hollywood Reporter reported that Tarantino shelved The Movie Critic, long assumed to be his 10th and final film, about a 1970s porn-rag critic named Jim Sheldon, with rumored casting that drifted from Paul Walter Hauser to Brad Pitt to Tom Cruise and reportedly morphed into another Cliff Booth story. Sean's take: he keeps telling Tarantino to drop the 10-movies rule, and Once Upon a Time in Hollywood was already a near-perfect note to have ended on at nine."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Irishman",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Sean frames Scorsese's reported Sinatra biopic (Leonardo DiCaprio as Frank, Jennifer Lawrence as Ava Gardner) as a possible capstone to the gangster arc that runs Goodfellas, Casino, The Irishman, with the entertainment industry as the last frontier the mob infiltrates. His worry: it's a music biopic, and this plus a rumored second Scorsese Jesus film (Andrew Garfield and Miles Teller attached) both sound like they've had 'some meetings' and not much else."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "A Soft Preview of ‘Abigail’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Abigail",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sean saw it and walks through the marketing problem: it opens as a straight abduction thriller (six archetypal criminals grab a millionaire's ballerina daughter and hold her in an old house) before the reveal, about an hour in, that Abigail is a vampire. The trailers give the vampire away, so you spend the whole first act waiting for a turn the film was written to hide. With Melissa Barrera, Dan Stevens, and Kathryn Newton."
        },
        {
          "title": "Imaginary",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The Blumhouse movie Amanda kept confusing with Abigail: the one about a girl and a possessed stuffed bear that slides across the floor. Sean saw it at a screening: 'not very good.' It sets off a long riff about killer Roombas and Amanda's refusal to own any Wi-Fi-enabled smart-home devices."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Sean’s 5 Most Anticipated",
      "note": "counted down 5 to 1",
      "subject": "summer 2024",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Furiosa: A Mad Max Saga",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 1, and the movie Sean says his whole summer is riding on. George Miller back in the Mad Max world with Anya Taylor-Joy and Chris Hemsworth; he was mixed on the trailer but says the CinemaCon footage was incredible."
        },
        {
          "title": "MaXXXine",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 2, and the one 'work of art' on his list. Ty West's third Mia Goth film after X and Pearl, a late-'70s/early-'80s LA serial-killer and porn-world drama, homage to B-exploitation and Heat. Cast includes Elizabeth Debicki, Michelle Monaghan, Bobby Cannavale, Halsey, Giancarlo Esposito, and Kevin Bacon."
        },
        {
          "title": "Alien: Romulus",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 3. Fede Álvarez (the Evil Dead remake) directing, with press-tour footage of him fawning over Ridley Scott. 'Do we need a seventh Alien movie? We don't need anything. Do I need it? I do.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Deadpool & Wolverine",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 4, arriving on Sean's birthday and the only Marvel movie of the year. Directed by Shawn Levy (Free Guy); the first MCU film outside the Spider-Verse he's been excited for since Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness, wary of the retcon housekeeping. Jennifer Garner reportedly back as Elektra."
        },
        {
          "title": "Kingdom of the Planet of the Apes",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 5, slotted in after Amanda goaded him into full 'moron mode' over the more respectable Kinds of Kindness. He loves the Reeves-era Apes films and plans to rewatch them all, bracing for a letdown."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Amanda’s 5 Most Anticipated",
      "note": "counted down 5 to 1",
      "subject": "summer 2024",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Twisters",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 1, actually a double feature with Richard Linklater's Hit Man, which Amanda names alongside it. Twisters is total moron mode (they're still firing radar sensors into tornadoes); Hit Man she hasn't seen but the trailer looked delightful, and she's all in on Glenn Powell, a stock she and Sean say they called back in 2017. Her vacation, annoyingly, coincides with the Twisters release."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Fall Guy",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 2. A big splashy action-romance built on movie stars, the kind of thing that barely exists anymore. She'll happily take Ryan Gosling grandstanding every six months; loved his SNL run, and she and Sean note his and Emily Blunt's chemistry."
        },
        {
          "title": "Trap",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 3. M. Night Shyamalan's Josh Hartnett thriller: goofy dad takes his daughter to a pop concert, then it turns. Amanda concedes the trailer may have already spent the whole hook, but she's forgiving of a Shyamalan high-concept premise even when the ending doesn't land."
        },
        {
          "title": "Fly Me to the Moon",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 4, her 'taking a chance' pick: an Apple romantic comedy with Scarlett Johansson and Channing Tatum set during the space race, staging a fake backup moon landing. She wants a movie-star romcom in the summer; last saw the pair together in Hail, Caesar!"
        },
        {
          "title": "Despicable Me 4",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 5, prompted by a story about her son deciding he's ready for the movies after silencing the room during The Sound of Music. She wishes it were a Minions movie instead (she's just not into Gru) but assumes it'll be one of the year's biggest films."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Honorable Mentions",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "A Quiet Place: Day One",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Michael Sarnoski (Pig) directing the prequel, with Lupita Nyong'o and Joseph Quinn. Sean's reservation: the power of the earlier films was being dropped into a world already adjusted to the horror, and an origin story gives that up."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Bikeriders",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Jeff Nichols' movie, which Sean saw and really liked at Telluride. Dropped by Fox, now opening via Focus. Part of a crowded June 21 slate of five indies alongside Kinds of Kindness, Fancy Dance, Janet Planet, and Thelma."
        },
        {
          "title": "Janet Planet",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Annie Baker's A24 debut with Julianne Nicholson, about mothers and daughters. The one 'respectable' pick Amanda had on her list before the Trap trailer dropped and she deleted it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Longlegs",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "A very disturbing Nicolas Cage horror movie Sean flags for its marketing; Amanda hadn't heard of it and would only see it if he asked."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Beach Boys",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "A Disney+ documentary both hosts are pumped for, not expecting Get Back, but a shared touchstone."
        },
        {
          "title": "Jim Henson: Idea Man",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Ron Howard's Disney+ documentary, which Sean, a self-described Henson dork, has already seen and loved: a fascinating, strange life."
        },
        {
          "title": "Inside Out 2",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Amanda's movie with her daughter. Not moron mode, but she cried at the first one."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
